II Experiment

II.1 Experimental Setup

The angular distribution of individual Î³ğ›¾\gamma-rays through the radiative capture reactions induced by epithermal neutrons was measured by introducing a pulsed neutron beam into the Accurate Neutronâ€“Nucleus Reaction Measurement Instrument (ANNRI) installed at the beamline BL04 of the Material and Life science experimental Facility (MLF) of the Japan Proton Accelerator Research Complex (J-PARC), as shown in Fig.Â 1Â IgashiraÂ etÂ al. (2009). The primary proton beam pulses were injected to the neutron production target in a single-bunch mode with a repetition rate of 25 Hz and an average beam power of 150 kW during the measurement. The disk chopper was operated synchronously with the proton injection for the suppression of low energy neutrons, to avoid frame overlap. The beam collimation was adjusted to define the neutron beam in a 222222 mm diameter circle on the target, placed at 21.521.521.5 m from the moderator surfaceÂ KinoÂ etÂ al. (2011). A lead plate (thickness: 37.537.537.5 mm) was placed in the upstream optics to suppress the Î³ğ›¾\gamma-ray background.

The zğ‘§z-axis is defined in the beam direction, the yğ‘¦y-axis is the vertical upward axis, and xğ‘¥x-axis is perpendicular to them, thus xâ€‹yâ€‹zğ‘¥ğ‘¦ğ‘§xyz forms a right-handed frame.

The assembly consisted of two types of detector units: Type-A (Fig.Â 3) and Type-B (Fig.Â 4).

Two combined seven Type-A detectors were placed above and below the target. The shape of the Type-A detector was hexagonal to enable clustering as shown in Fig.Â 3. The polar angles between the center of the target and the center of the crystal surface facing the target were Î¸=71âˆ˜ğœƒsuperscript71\theta=71^{\circ}, 90âˆ˜superscript9090^{\circ}, and 109âˆ˜superscript109109^{\circ}.

All germanium crystals were operated at a temperature of 777777 K. The typical energy resolution for the 1.3321.3321.332 MeV Î³ğ›¾\gamma-rays was 4.24.24.2 keV.

II.3 Angular Distribution

Hereafter, we concentrate on the 5161â€‹keV5161keV5161\,{\rm keV} transition to the ground state of 140La, in order to study the interference between the s- and p-wave amplitudes.

The photo-peak efficiency, including both the detection efficiency and the solid angle coverage, was readjusted using the photo-peak counts of the Î³ğ›¾\gamma-rays at EÎ³msubscriptsuperscriptğ¸mğ›¾E^{\rm m}_{\gamma}==5262â€‹keV5262keV5262\,{\rm keV} from the 14N(n,Î³)\gamma) reaction measured using the melamine target. It can be reasonably assumed that the Î³ğ›¾\gamma-rays are emitted isotropically, as the 14N does not have any resonance below 400â€‹eV400eV400\,{\rm eV} and p-wave or higher angular momentum components of the incident neutron is negligibly small in this energy region.

The photo-peak counts of the 5161â€‹keV5161keV5161\,{\rm keV} transition were determined by subtracting the background counts caused by Compton scattering of the more energetic Î³ğ›¾\gamma-rays from targets other than the lanthanum target. To evaluate the background, two energy regions were used: (I) 5200â€‹keV5200keV5200\,{\rm keV}â‰¤\leqEÎ³msubscriptsuperscriptğ¸mğ›¾E^{\rm m}_{\gamma}â‰¤\leq5290â€‹keV5290keV5290\,{\rm keV} and (II) 4900â€‹keV4900keV4900\,{\rm keV}â‰¤\leqEÎ³msubscriptsuperscriptğ¸mğ›¾E^{\rm m}_{\gamma}â‰¤\leq4980â€‹keV4980keV4980\,{\rm keV}. The contribution of Compton scattering of Î³ğ›¾\gamma-rays corresponding to the three photo-peaks are contained in region (II). The amount of this contribution from Compton scattering is estimated using the response function ÏˆÂ¯Â¯ğœ“\bar{\psi} given in Eq.Â 30 and obtained by simulation. The background in region (II) is estimated by subtracting the Compton contribution from the Î³ğ›¾\gamma-ray counts in region (II). The background is estimated using a best-fit third-order polynomial of EÎ³msubscriptsuperscriptğ¸mğ›¾E^{\rm m}_{\gamma} in regions (I) and (II).

There still remains a possible contamination of prompt Î³ğ›¾\gamma-rays from impurities overlapping with the 5161â€‹keV5161keV5161\,{\rm keV} photo-peak. The possible contamination was examined over the entire pulse height spectrum, and was determined to be less than 0.08%percent0.080.08\% of the photo-peak. The possibility of contamination was neglected as the determined upper limit of 0.08%percent0.080.08\% is smaller than the statistical error of the photo-peak.

V Conclusion

We observed clear angular distribution of emitted Î³ğ›¾\gamma-rays in the transition from the p-wave resonance of 139La+n to the ground state of 140La as a function of incident neutron energy. The angular distribution was analyzed by assuming interference between s- and p-wave amplitudes, and the partial neutron width of the p-wave resonance was obtained. This result suggests that the T-violating effect can be enhanced on the same order of the P-violating effect for 0.74Â eV p-wave resonance of 139La+n. Therefore an experiment to explore T-violation in compound nuclear states is feasible. In addition, the analysis under this assumption leads to results that are consistent with theoretical expectation, and we therefore believe the assumption of s-p mixing is correct.
